steel on the skyline 
sky made of glass 
made for a real world 
all things must pass

oo-o 
waiting for something 
looking for someone 
is there no reason? 
have i stared too long?

oo-o
oo-o 
you say you'll leave me
and when the sun is low
and the rays high 
i can see it now 
i can feel it die 
oo-o
oo-o

david bowie

text:
it is not survivor's behavior, circumstances, or identity that causes gendered violence. violence against women has deep roots in societal disrespect towards women and commodification of our bodies. to end violence against women, we must challenge the very definition of masculinity.
.
.
.

text:

text:
got to witness the most amazing panel yesterday, thanks to @leewayfound, @temple_contemp, and #reatajiri who brought our whole mfa cohort: â€œthe pleasure principle: finding pleasure in the age of #metoo,â€ featuring the founder of the #metoo movement herself, @taranajaneen, in conversation with @favianna1 and moderated by @thefatsextherapist, who is my new favorite hero!! i also got to meet everybody afterwards (swipe to see fan-femme pics with tarana, sonalee, and my fellow first year @julijackson, who sat right next to me through this whole righteous thing, and shared many #fuckyeah moments with me). this is the next step in the #metoo movement - finding pleasure in our survivor bodies while we also hold and process and digest our pain. i have always, always seen pleasure as a healing act and held desire as my compass and iâ€™m so glad to see that prominent social justice folx and connecting that to their and our movement building communities. also, tarana burke has a non-binary child, and hearing her talk about their journey together brought tears to their eyes (this was what we were connecting over in the second pic). these femmes are fierce and i highly recommend keeping an eye out for the video of this talk that will be released to the public soon. also, psa: pleasure and pain are intertwined. we may all feel broken and disconnected intermittently or permanently in our lives, and there is no right way to heal. but if we can access everyday pleasure in our daily lives we can start to build a bridge to joy. and this doesnâ€™t mean #$elfcare spa packages; it means watching law and order in your pajamas, or cultivating awesome friendships, or wearing a sweater we feel cute in as we do the dirtier, harder work of composting this capitalist shit heap of a system that bears down on us all. and, yes, iâ€™m a survivor, and i thank my decade+ long journey for leading me to a place of feeling really great in my body at least once a day. okay love you all ğŸ’•ğŸ¥ğŸ’¯
ğŸŒˆ

text:
this afternoon i am feeling productive.

how often do you use â€œfineâ€, â€œgoodâ€, â€œbadâ€ or â€œokâ€ as feeling words?  they really arenâ€™t good descriptors of how one is feeling - they are vague and noncommittal.

some clients have shared that they use those 4 words as feeling words because they do not know what they are feeling.  or, they do not know how to identify their feelings.  some clients like more neutral words because they donâ€™t like â€œbad feelingsâ€. .

probably not too surprising, i do not view feelings as good versus bad. i think of experiencing all feelings to be important. not important because some feelings are unpleasant, but because if we donâ€™t feel sadness, how can we really experience joy; if we donâ€™t feel fear, how do we understand contentment; and so on. .

letâ€™s learn to expand our feeling vocabulary!  letâ€™s break some of our family rules (or ed rules) that we are only allowed to express certain feelings! letâ€™s learn to identify what we are feeling and why!

this color feelings wheel was designed by dr. gloria willcox.  it can be downloaded and printed.  if identifying feelings is difficult for you, i encourage you to begin learning what you are feeling.  feelings are not as scary as we think they are.  itâ€™s can be quite liberating to be able to identify a feeling and understand why we are feeling that way, and how to change it! ğŸ’œ

text:
episode 20 with nubia duvall wilson, published author
ğŸ“šwe had a soulful conversation about her book, the survivorâ€™s club.
ğŸ¤nubia shared her experience as a survivor of abuse and her work to help other survivors get the support they need.
ğŸ’›this is the perfect book for a â€œbook club for busy peopleâ€ - itâ€™s a short read that will lead to a big conversation. 
this episode is fully an immersion into the interview with nubia. she is candid about her experiences and all of the emotions that she felt and still feels when there is a triggering event, like the supreme court justice nomination a couple of months ago. our focus moved to mental health, having compassion for oneself and others, and coping with the strong emotions that come long after the trauma is over. we both hope that this podcast helps you understand, start a conversation, or gives you hope that you can survive and thrive after trauma. $5.00 from each book sold goes to charity:

text:
what are the connections between #metoo, healing, sexual pleasure, orgasm, and being in fulfilling relationships? watch this video featuring a groundbreaking conversation between metoo movement founder, @taranajaneen tarana burke, and myself, moderated by sex therapist, @thefatsextherapist sonalee rashatwar. our dialogue felt so good and i emerged from our conversation feeling full, many attendees shared with us that they got ideas on how they better love themselves and bring more joy and pleasure into their lives. as people affected by systemic oppression, historical trauma and patriarchy - to claim one's joy and to be deliberate with feeling ourselves in our bodies is an act of liberation. thank you @leewayfound leeway foundation for hosting this! 
link to video: bit.ly/pleasureprinciple2018

the topics we discussed from a cis femme woc perspective included:
- relationships - sex toys
- healing from sexual assault
- strategies to practice more fulfilling relationships
- fat bodies and pleasure
- desirability
- white supremacy
- clitoral orgasm
- sex parties
- getting your body's needs met
- queer and non queer love and negotiation
- masturbation

recently, secretary of education betsy devos released new title ix guidelines.

we are concerned that the proposed guidelines provide more protections for the accused. additionally, the proposed guidelines make it more difficultÂ for survivors of sexual violence to report harassment and assault by narrowing the definition of sexual misconduct.

all students k-12 and beyond deserve to grow up safe, respected, and valued. under these new proposals, fewer students may report gender-basedÂ violence and many will be denied equal access to education. in the wake of #metoo and #timesup, schools must do more, not less, to protect every studentâ€™s right to safety on campus.

the department of education is currently accepting feedback during its sixty-day notice and comment period, which ends in january.

we are calling on survivors, advocates, and allies to make their voices heard.

you can submit your comments online here:Â www.regulations.gov

or you can mail them to:

brittany bull
u.s. department of education
400 maryland avenue s.w.
room 6e310
washington, d.c. 20202

please include the docket id no. ed-2018-ocr-0064 in the reference line of your comment.

text:
long before #metoo became the catalyst for a womenâ€™s movement about sexual assault â€” and a decade before the fall of #harveyweinstein, #billcosby and u.s. olympic gymnastics doctor larry nassar â€” there was jeffrey edward epstein.

epstein, a multimillionaire hedge fund manager whose friends included a constellation of entertainers, #politicians, business titans and royalty, for yearsÂ lured teenage girls to his palm beach mansion as part of a cult-like sex pyramid scheme, police in the town of #palmbeach found.

the girls arrived, sometimes by taxi, for trysts at all hours of the day and night. few were told much more than that they would be paid to give an old man a massage â€” and that he might ask them to strip down to their underwear or get naked. but what began as a massage often led to masturbation, oral sex, intercourse and other sex acts, police and court records show. the alleged abuse dates back to 2001 and went on for years.

in 2007, despite ample physical #evidence and multiple witnesses corroborating the girlsâ€™ stories, federal prosecutors and epsteinâ€™s lawyers quietly put together a remarkable deal for #epstein, then 54. he agreed to plead guilty to two felony prostitution charges in state court, and in exchange, he and his accomplices received immunity from federal #sextrafficking charges that could have sent him to prison for life.

he served 13 months in a private wing of the #palmbeachcounty stockade.Â his alleged co-conspirators, who helped schedule his sex sessions, were never prosecuted.
(video miami herald)

text: been thinking about gender-based violence a lot these days (more than usual, which is a lot). a friend asked if iâ€™d be comfortable sharing my experiences for a video production and itâ€™s been a handful to process... i also had a nasty encounter with an acquaintance recently that resurfaced all these feelings. the statistics feel so cold and removed from the flesh and blood of the reality... they also just never seem to add up to the people i know, the stories iâ€™ve heard. i have yet to meet a single queer person, woman, or person of trans experience that has not been the victim of either physical, emotional, psychological or sexual violence. if you know of someone, though, please let me know. iâ€™d love to be proven wrong on this one. #genderbasedviolence #violence #stats #wtf #metoo

text:
today is national remembrance of violence against women day, so today on the blog we are highlighting our client cynthia's* story. 
it took cynthia three months to make the decision to pick up the phone and call evelyn skeete, transitional and housing support worker at yorktown. â€œwhen i called evelyn, she didnâ€™t get into trying to make an appointment with me; she just said, â€˜you are welcome to come right away.â€™ i went that day and met with evelyn who shared a lot of information with me. evelyn never pried. i could tell she had a lot of experience working with women who have gone through similar experiences. she was extremely knowledgeable and she meant business; i knew she could help me,â€ says, cynthia.

read cynthia's full story and learn more about yorktown's violence against women services by clicking the link in our bio. #myactionsmatter #metoo #yorktownfamilyservices #vaw #violenceagainstwomen

text:
the crucible_mary warren (2/2)

hello folks, it's #monologuethursday! this week i am proposing you an excerpt from "the crucible" by arthur miller, a play based on the salem witch hunt. this is the segment in which mary warren, in order to divert the suspects lingering on her, accuses sarah good of witchcraft; miller depicts warren as a weak character, but i decided to go for a different choice: instead of simple weakness, i wanted to show the malice of cowardice, and this not just because of some supposed artistic licence, but because i believe that in hard times there is no excuse for acts like warren's. and i feel that, once again, miller's play is more contemporary then he could imagine: he wrote it as a critique against maccartism, but things haven't really changed. people keep turning in the neighbor, blaming on the weakest, on the diverse, on  immigrants, on women not even their own "sins", but sins that belong to those who command them. weakness and cowardice have always been amongst the most powerful weapons that the people simply hand to their leaders, and it has always led to disaster. and i feel that cowards are even more to blame that tyrants for that disaster, because they kill their brothers and sisters for nothing but their misareble nature.

in hard times we must stay tight, we must stick together and find the courage to defend our dignity throigh the love for each other.
always.
#agirlfromtheislandinnewyork
girlfromtheislandinnewyork

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text_retweet:
i've decided to repost this, so many of you have probably seen this before. the reasons i had for deleting my posts are not as important as the reasons i had for posting in the first place. so many of us are struggling in the same ways, and i am here to help anyone who needs it! â¤ï¸ one day this body will be mine again. one day i will be able to look at myself and like what i see. i thought things would be better by now. i thought i would love myself and my body again. i don't. i have spent over a year feeling as if i'm in someone else's body, and it's a body i hate. i hate everything about this body. its face. its stomach. its legs. ever since i realized what you were doing to me, it's felt like there is something that has infected my body. i want to just forget everything you did and reset my life. i guess that's just what abuse and rape does to you. 
after months of struggling, i have finally realized that it isn't going away. pretending like it didn't happen won't change anything, and it won't heal me. this needs to be talked about. this is my story to tell, and keeping it a secret isn't helping anyone. i get it though. i really do. it's not a fun to topic to talk about or even hear about. i get it. it's scary to think about these things happening. to think that the people you consider heroes, close friends, or even family could do such things to you or someone else is a terrifying thought. but this is happening. it has happened, and unfortunately, it will keep happening as long as we a stay quiet. i lied to myself for a very long time about what was happening, so i get it. 
so to anyone else struggling with this, we will get through this. we will overcome what was done to us. we will rebuild and become stronger than ever, and i will be here for anyone else struggling. 
and to the person who hurt me, while you're out believing you're a hero saving lives and putting out fires, i'll be rebuilding myself from the fire you put me through, and i will come out better than ever, loving myself and my body. and one day i'll even wear my favorite clothes again â¤ï¸ #awareness #metoo #sexualassault #survivor

text:
i can not begin to express my excitement with what it is i am doing. i believe with every fibre of my being that i am walking out the calling on my life. all glory to god. 
the vision is crystal clear.
i am championing restoration and redemption in the lives of women by speaking into and calling forth their full potential as daughters of the king.
it is a time to take the misrepresentation of the gospel that has happened over and over and wounded so many, to come to a stop. it will not only be by words, it will be by action. a new wineskin. it is time for women to stand softly and strong in who they were created to be by him, for it is what this world needs desperately.

text:
#winning #howitsdone â€” rep. #betoorourke (d-texas) met last month with former #presidentobama, just days after the texas democrat lost his senate race against sen. ted cruz (r), the washington post reported tuesday.
-
the meeting was held nov. 16 at obama's offices in washington, d.c., amid speculation that o'rourke could launch a white house bid for 2020.
-
o'rourke has received praise from several #obama's allies who said they see similarities between the former president and o'rourke.
-
obama has called o'rourke an "impressive young man" in a recent interview "the axe files" podcast, hosted by obama's former strategist, david axelrod.
-
"it felt as if he based his statements and his positions on what he believed," obama said of o'rourke's senate campaign. "and that, you'd like to think, is normally how things work. sadly it's not."
-
o'rourke was narrowly defeated last month in his effort to unseat cruz, but he is viewed as a possible frontrunner for the 2020 democratic nomination. he has said he is considering a presidential run.
-
one recent poll showed o'rourke trailing only former vice president #joebiden and sen. #berniesanders (i-vt.) among potential 2020 democratic candidates.
â€”
#equality #healthcare #metoo #truth #fuckhaters #barackobama #obama #lgbtq #historyrepeats #racism #immigration #dumptrump #fucktrump #lincoln #abrahamlincoln #betoforpresident thanks!

text:
over the past year, the metoo movement has created important dialogue around sexual assault and the culture of silence that enables sexual abuse and violence to thrive. today, bhd joins the conversation and focuses explicitly on sexual assault and violence in the black community by interviewing dr. carolyn west, an award-winning author and professor of psychology at the university of washington. during the interview, dr. west provides insight into what constitutes sexual assault, the history of sexual violence against black women, the factors that shape disclosure, and the trauma and grief associated with sexual violence. after complicating the distinction between victim and perpetrator, we discuss her latest project on the images of black women in pornography, the negative consequences of those images on women and men, and sex trafficking in the black community. we close by having a conversation about how to change the culture around sexual assault and the images of black women in the media.

text:
i am so glad for #jhtoo and to be surrounded by other likeminded, supportive people who stand up for survivors and stand up for equality. everyone who spoke and came out today is incredibly brave. i believe her. say it loud, say "me too," jhu, we're watching you. 
here is the link to the obarrio petition, which i am proud to say already has over 1,400 signatures: https://docs.google.com/forms/d/e/1faipqlscc1i8rx9uc3cbj0bijxhkphosmzebfndk6fgbvdxxy30q2hw/viewform?fbclid=iwar1cq1lw_8mh2bkv9ymmsf-hkdg-34vhn92ohdzag9zqwyjbbjnc7_ouekk

also, here is the link to betsy devos's new proposed title ix policy. it has made a lot of significant changes which will make it easier on the perpetrators and harder on the survivors. i encourage you to look it over (and am more than happy to answer any questions about it). the public commenting period is anytime before 1/28/2019 so if you are interested in learning more about the policy and/or sharing your thoughts with the federal register about title ix, you can go to this link to provide devos with official comments about her proposed changes to title ix here anytime before 1/28/2019:  https://www.federalregister.gov/documents/2018/11/29/2018-25314/nondiscrimination-on-the-basis-of-sex-in-education-programs-or-activities-receiving-federal

text:
1,400 public high school and middle school students in lovington, nm heard me speak today in 2 assemblies. they were wonderful! and iâ€™m so proud of the many boys and girls who came forward for their own life changing #metoo moment today. so much courage. and iâ€™m grateful for the brave, compassionate friends who stepped up to be a voice and a support for someone else. this is the generation our world needs!

personally, iâ€™ll forever be inspired by the 7th grade boy who came to my book table and shared that, like me, he had always wanted to run away from home. my heart went out to him and i asked him if he still struggles with that and he said â€œnot anymore.â€ so i then asked him what had helped him to overcome (assuming he meant that it was in his past) and he answered, â€œyou.â€ ğŸ˜­ 
tears fell straight from my eyes to the tile floor. 
these speaking tours take everything i have to give, but these kids and their future are worth every pinch of it. 
thank you god for another amazing day. tomorrow morning we #breakthesilence and spread hope at another hs and ms and then a community wide awareness event in the evening. i appreciate all of your prayers and support and love. #onevoice #together

my beautiful friend takes me to see faust at dramaten/elverket and afterwards we can not stop talking about the thoughts provoked: about power play, the desire to have and own, about fear, about looking away although you see it, about not listening although you hear it. we talk about boundaries: for evil, forgiveness, for how long you can stand yourself when you don't speak up. and that when you do, you often end up very lonely. we talk about punishment, acceptance, about  choosing a standpoint â€” how important it is, and how hard it is to do.

i was molested when i was in 6th grade by my cousins uncle. i used to live in a joint family household. so, whenever he came to visit my cousins family, he would somehow manage to find me alone. at first, i didnâ€™t know exactly what was going on or what he was trying to do, but i tried to stop him every time because i knew it wasnâ€™t right. it wasnâ€™t something i wore or i didnâ€™t give him â€œthe signalâ€ or i didnâ€™t ask for it. i was a fucking 12 year old kid going through puberty. he would grab my breast and twist them as hard as he can. i would try to push him away and run away from him, but nothing seemed to work. it was a feeling that iâ€™ll never forget. i would cry in pain at night, but it wasnâ€™t the pain of my tender breast that made me cry, it was the pain in my heavy heart. and i would ask god â€œwhy me?â€ then be thankful to god because i didnâ€™t get raped. 
i finally decided to tell my mom and the look on her face was unforgettable. i can already see she felt helpless. she was silent, then i said â€œammu please can i call 911 and get him arrested?â€ and my mom said â€œno.â€ at that very moment my heart broke into so many pieces that i became numb. it hurt the most because i felt betrayed by my own mother. she didnâ€™t want to â€œruinâ€ my reputation or my future, especially because i didnâ€™t have a father. she didnâ€™t want anyone to question our family because we come from a â€œwell known, respected familyâ€. i was angry at my mom for couple of days, then i put myself in her shoes and saw what she was going through as a mother. my mom got scared, being a widow and an immigrant with three kids in a bengali society was not easy. my mom loves me with everything and she became my shield. so, i kept my mouth shut for all these years. 
i was contemplating if i should post this or not. i kept asking myself, what would people say? what if my future family doesnâ€™t accept me for this? what if no one believes me? then, i realized thatâ€™s the exact reason why my mom never said anything and i didnâ€™t want to be that person. i have every right to speak up for myself. i am more than just a body. i am strong, stronger than ever. i am a woman and that is my superpower.

text:
it has been a little over one year since the beginning of the #metoo movement. as one of the main goals of the movement is to create an environment more prone to supporting victims of sexual harassment, progress can arguably be quantified by the number of sexual harassment charges filed annually. 
compared to the 5-year average, this past year saw a significant rise in charges filed with the eeoc, increasing over 12%. similarly, lawsuits filed by the eeoc increased 50% while successful mediation proceedings rose by 43%. with stats like these i would say the movement has made some important progress so far, and i hope to see continued growth throughout 2019. 
sources: u.s. equal employment opportunity commission

text: this leaf is my leaf. âœ¨ğŸŒ± the first survivor leaf entry i wrote one night when i couldnâ€™t sleep. all three of my stories are written here. iâ€™m proud of this leaf. while each of these experiences was born in pain, i have come so far since these darknesses in my life. iâ€™ve pushed through fear, anxiety, shame, guilt- and iâ€™m still here. gone are shame and guilt (iâ€™m still working on fear and anxiety, and thatâ€™s okay. work is progress!), and iâ€™ve finally found a way to come back into the light. survivorship is something that never goes away- iâ€™ll never be able to erase these memories.  but i have transformed their power over me. i painted, i wrote, i created, and i grew them into something beautiful. i was recently speaking to a friend and fellow survivor and told her that, while there have been times in my past that i have felt empowered *in spite of* being a survivor, i have never felt empowered *because* i am a survivor- until now. this work is changing me. âœ¨ğŸŒ± click the link in my bio to contribute your story to the survivor tree. #rapesurvivor #survivor #survivoradvocate #survivorselfcare #metoo #whyididntreport #drchristineblaseyford #endrapeculture #believewomen #believesurvivors #believeblackwomen #timesup #artist #wip #workinprogress #thesurvivortreeproject

hello, loves! â£â£
â£â£
iâ€™m working on a new project to be launched in october for #domesticviolenceawarenessmonth. and i need your help. â£â£
â£â£
the focus of this project is to bring awareness to victim-blaming. itâ€™s something that iâ€™m extremely passionate about. i personally was victim-blamed a countless amount of times. as a victim-turned-advocate, i feel the need to shed light upon this topic. â£â£
â£â£
i can go on and on about my story, but it is not enough. in order to make a differenceâ€” the world needs to hear your stories, too. â£â£
â£â£
if you are a survivor: have you ever been victim-blamed? what was specifically said and/or done to you? â£â£
â£â£
in the comments below, tell me exactly what was said to you, quote-on-quote by someone who didnâ€™t believe your survivor story. this is open to anyone who has been the victim of domestic violence, child abuse and/or sexual assault. â£â£
â£â£
to give some examples: â£â£
â£â£
â€œyou werenâ€™t abused. give me a break.â€â£â£
â£â£
â€œhe only hit you once. big deal.â€â£â£
â£â£
â€œbut, what did you do to provoke him to do that?â€ â£â£
â£â£
these are all examples of victim-blaming/victim-shaming. have similar words been said to you? if so, please contribute to this project. use your voice. tell your story. letâ€™s put an end to victim-shaming. â£â£
â£
thank you. â£
â£â£

text:
their waiting room is cozy and they have fresh coffee. the desk people smiled, but not in that weird way. 
i could easily move forward in my life and not work through these things.
i'm addressing my #mst experience because i realized how much it impacted me. it impacted relationships with myself and others, my ability to know what safe is, to choose healthy people to be around, to be kind to myself, to feel as if my body was my own, how i felt about #integrity, the #military, christianity, and #america.
it changed my life path. i need to look at that. i want to. 
i want to level up in life. 
#mst #armyofone #lifeismessy #newnormal #youareworthit #rapeculture #metoo #veteran #metoomilitary #timesup

text:
"i was about 14 years old, travelling in the bus with a friend after school for the first time on our own. we were excited as this was a little adventure to us. the excitement didn't last long however, when we were approached by an elderly man. he was standing behind us and first started by attempting to talk to us, to which we ignored. he then whispered lewd, explicit comments which subsequently lead to him pushing against and rubbing his genitals on me. i froze with fear. i couldn't move nor confront him. i became completely numb. my friend realized what was happening but i knew she was too scared to react. tears started rolling down my face and i felt helpless. this act continued for a while and finally when a lady noticed, and offered me her seat, the perpetrator got off the bus. none of the bystanders intervened, and for days i couldn't overcome my fear. i was traumatized. i didn't tell my parents, thinking they would never allow me to travel in a bus again, nor spoke to my friends as i was ashamed. my friend and i promised each other that this would be a secret. little did i know then, that all my life i would have to go through similar experiences whenever i use public transport" - janani.

if you witness sexual harassment in public transport: intervene. speak up. be the change.

text:
at least two of the country's biggest radio operators â€” rogers media and bell media â€” say they've decided to pull the controversial christmas favourite out of their rotations this year.
that comes as the duet, written back in 1944, faces renewed scrutiny over what some say are inappropriate lyrics in the wake of the #metoo movement.
earlier this week, cleveland radio station wdok-fm announced it was no longer playing the song in response to listener feedback. some took issue over lyrics where one singer is trying to persuade the other to stay inside, with exchanges that include, "what's in this drink?" and "baby, don't hold out."
bell media spokesman scott henderson says the company, which runs two 24-hour christmas stations in vancouver and ottawa, chose not to include the christmas tune on its playlists this year.
"the song wasn't scheduled for airplay on any bell media radio stations and there are no plans to play it in the future," he wrote in an emailed statement.

source: huffingtonpost.ca

text:
today, i finished â€˜south of forgivenessâ€™, by thordis elva and thomas stranger. *disclaimer* sandi toksvig praised it and iâ€™m obsessed with her.
.
.
there are 7,200 seconds in two hours. cape town is the rape capital of the world. 7/10 rapes are committed by someone known to the victim.
.
.
this controversial collaboration is a book for everyone.
.
.
possibly the most important thing i shall read this year. i cannot begin to comprehend the lasting implications someone feels having been subjected to sexual violence. this book has however, shown me both the stark reality of it within our society, and the catastrophic effects upon both the survivor and perpetrator.
.
.
whilst reading this book iâ€™ve had various conversations with male and female friends about sexual violence within our current culture. 
how much do we know? 
what are we doing to tackle it? 
is it deeply rooted within inequality?
.
.
this stunning narrative through the spectacular sites of cape town presents the inescapable truth that your place within society dictates whether or not you can even report the crime that youâ€™ve been subjected to.
.
.
the level of honesty within this book has completely and utterly astounded me. weâ€™re all vulnerable. with the #metoo and #timesup movements are we entering a society ready to change?
.
.
thank you @thordiselva

text:
stable talk | peace, participation and patriarchy

speaker | dr. swarna rajagopalan : political scientist, consultant and writer.

curated by | @warhorse_wh 
giving her audience a thorough run-down on patriarchy from an academic sense and from a perspective of daily life. she explained the features of patriarchy (privilege, entitlement, impunity and exclusion) and how patriarchy sets up imaginary binaries. she also made a profound and convincing argument about how patriarchy is equivalent to violence. the talk concluded with her explaining on how to go about handling the #metoo movement.

look into my eyes he tells her
iâ€™m gonna say goodbye he says yea
do not cry she begs of him goodbye yea
all that day she thinks of his love yea

they whip him through the streets and alleys there
the gormless and the baying crowd right there
they canâ€™t get enough of that doomsday song
they canâ€™t get enough of it all

listen

listen to the whores he tells her
he fashions paper sculptures of them
then drags them to the riverâ€˜s bank in the cart
their soggy paper bodies wash ashore in the dark
and the priest stiff in hate now demanding fun begin
of his women dressed as men for the pleasure of that priest

here i am
not quite dying
my body left to rot in a hollow tree
its branches throwing shadows
on the gallows for me

and the next

text:
@thejimmydoreshow @bbcnews @nbcnews @anakasparianofficial @turunsanomat wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
@radiohelsinki @katyturnbc @huffpostitalia @foxnews for those 87 million people probably wondering what was actually done with their data, i went back to christopher wylie, the ex-cambridge analytica employee who blew the whistle on the companyâ€™s problematic operations in the observer. according to wylie, all you need to know is a little bit about data science, a little bit about bored rich women, and a little bit about human psychology.

step one, he says, over the phone as he scrambles to catch a train: - when youâ€™re building an algorithm, you first need to create a training set. that is: no matter what you want to use fancy data science to discover, you first need to gather the old-fashioned way. before you can use facebook likes to predict a personâ€™s psychological profile, you need to get a few hundred thousand people to do a 120-question personality quiz.

the â€œtraining setâ€ refers, then, to that data in its entirety: the facebook likes, the personality tests, and everything else you want to learn from. most important, it needs to contain your â€œfeature setâ€: - the underlying data that you want to make predictions on, wylie says. - in this case, itâ€™s facebook data, but it could be, for example, text, like natural language, or it could be clickstream data â€“ the complete record of your browsing activity on the web. - those are all the features that you want to [use to] predict. at the other end, you need your target variables, the things that youâ€™re trying to predict for. so in this case, personality traits or political orientation, or what have you.

alex hern
the guardian

@radiohelsinki @katyturnbc @huffpostitalia @foxnews bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
our second script-development #workshop took place in #kathmandu at the end of november. with us we had #theatre practitioners and veterans, visual and performance artists, and slam poetsâ€”many of whom have been working on #genderbasedviolence and the lives of women in different ways. 
the discussions were strongly influenced by the #nirmalapant rape and murder case which has had #nepal in a ferment since july. the participants drew parallels between the #impunity of the government in current democratic nepal and the impunity of the royal family in the case of the #namitasunitahatyakando when nepal was a constitutional monarchy, 37 years ago. across a gulf of over thirty years, the same hush-up, mass #protests and no solution. 
we discussed how violence exists on a continuumâ€”from the extreme #violence of #rape to the ordinariness of #streetharassment. 
this video has yukta of @wordwarriorsnepal talking about #streetharassment, taking #publictransport and the tendency of male friends to react with #notallmen in a #metoo world. 
we'll be releasing more material from the workshop over the next few weeks so stay tuned for more #exitimpunity. 
in the meantime, tell us your thoughts on what yukta says here. do you also feel like anyone can be a harasser? if you're a man, how do you react to remarks like this? how do you feel about the continuous self-monitoring and self-regulation we often do as women occupying public space?

#zubaanbooks #endsexualviolence #breakthesilence #feminist #theatre #feministart #womensrights #feministpractice #impunity #accesstojustice #feminism

text:
today is the 5 year anniversary of an extremely painful experience that completely changed the trajectory of my life. at the time, i felt like a fraud anyway, so it made some kind of warped sense to me that i shouldn't have happiness and that i couldn't achieve the goals i had set myself. today, as i reminisce, i am so #grateful. for where i am now, for who i am, for everything i lost (because it wasn't mine to keep), for everything i've gained in the process - & for the fact that i now believe in myself and my own value. i am no longer the same person. and for that i am so #grateful.

speaking about your experiences and emotions will assist you in processing events that have occurred in your life.

if you feel your story may be too much for someone else to carry, verbalise it without an audience. just speak aloud everything has happened and finish when you reach where you are today. 
this process can help you to see your progress and what events you need to work on.

you are not alone in this, you have been there all along to witness your journey.

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

in his first post-white house interviews, steve bannon, the rightwing ideologue who helped propel donald trump to the white house, made clear that he had no intention of going quietly. - iâ€™ve got my hands back on my weapons, the former white house chief strategist, who returned as executive chairman of breitbart news late friday afternoon, told the weekly standard. - i built a f***ing machine at breitbart. and now iâ€™m about to go back, knowing what i know, and weâ€™re about to rev that machine up. and rev it up we will do.

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trumpâ€™s election, trumpeted the return of their â€œpopulist heroâ€ on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publicationâ€™s announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if thereâ€™s any confusion out there, let me clear it up: iâ€™m leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents â€“ on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

julia carrie wong
the guardian

americans are awake. thatâ€™s what my boyfriend said yesterday afternoon when he started getting 3 hate msg-s per minute. 
there is a whole outrage in the usa art circles right now, because of borisâ€™s art. by presuming, projecting, jumping to conclusions, and overall superficiality, idea that he is a racist has been formed and spread with the light speed of the instagram. 
his art is provocative, he uses humor and racist symbols to expose the hypocrisy. 
looking at it superficially, you would read it as racist without doubt. thatâ€™s where instagram, a perfect tool for idiotizing the people, comes in handy. to look at everything for one second and form the opinion based on that one second. on the other hand, if you would dive in deeper, you would see how he manipulates observers into a complicated emotional game, bringing out the subconscious ideas, fears and other emotions that get buried under the weight of a taboo. in this case racism and immigration.
we could argue weather itâ€™s good or bad, weather it works or not, but iâ€™m not here to defend his art.

what i want to talk about is political correctness and itâ€™s evolution from correctional tool for malign social behavior, into a strong censorship tool, bordering fascism.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think itâ€™s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people donâ€™t necessarily know itâ€™s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so itâ€™s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that youâ€™re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of peopleâ€™s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldnâ€™t have seen, and couldnâ€™t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, â€œwould work for anyoneâ€. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean theyâ€™re mercenaries. theyâ€™ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

itâ€™s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing â€“ at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public â€“ our intimate family connections, our â€œlikesâ€, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole thatâ€™s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

text:
@arimelber @maddowshow @seanhannity i've watched the qspiracy since the beginning.

steve bannon left the wh august last year and q appeared the following october. do you believe in coincidences?

abusing and leaking presidential information to mislead the people and benefit the hijacked party of puppets is obviously just business as usual.

however - while doing this djt with the brave bunch known as gop has willingly opened a pussy wound that anyone around the world can easily contaminate. i like to call it meddlin' with presidental blessin'. i'm not the only one who knows this opportunity and messes with the bombastic patriots - may be russia or china or mbs or antifa or me me me, a tiny quarter pounder sitting on my bed.

the whole qshow seems like a vile roleplay but instead it has become the heart of the propaganda operation that joseph goebbels would have died for. it is obvious that stuff like pizzagateâ„¢ was testing and groundwork for the 2016 election and since it proved to be very effective it is used still, today, right now.

the accompanying memes go way beyond the propaganda of nsdap. social media companies are just helpless with the fake content - there is no way they are going to risk their business by taking a real responsibility.

there is absolutely no way that gop isn't aware of what is going on - after all cambridge analytica worked for ted cruz and john bolton. the whole narrative is built on the same user data that bannon and the mercers reportedly got from cambridge analytica.

and here comes the best part. trumq is truly playing along with his tweets, gestures and words.

the bigger issue still is that requqlicans are willingly piggybacking this lunacy and abusing the faith of their fellow men while campaigning for the midterms. this is not just an insane national security risk - it's a leaking conspiracy and treason in plain sight.

a non

text:
@ylex @nyt.fi @nytimes bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

@maaseuduntulevaisuus @burgerking @arimelber @maddowshow @seanhannity bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

the trans-siberian railwayâ €
the projectâ€™s financial and technical challenges were immense, and construction proved to be a nightmare. the harsh siberian climate hampered progress all along. large rivers had to be bridged, and large extensions of land were either waterlogged or unyielding permafrost. the lack of labor in remote places meant that soldiers, conscripts and gulag prisoners had to be brought in. up to 90,000 men were employed in the construction.â €

text:
when is the last time you thanked yourself, your entire being, for all of the ways youâ€™ve been able to navigate life up until this point? 
itâ€™s easy to get lost in frustrations about things weâ€™re struggling with and circumstances we wish were different. but for thirty seconds, a few breaths in and out, can you feel what itâ€™s like to just sink into yourself with a full heart and say â€œiâ€™m still here.â€ we are incredible and resilient beings. complicated and so damn worthy. 
our systems by nature do whatever they can to help us persevere through traumatic events to keep us alive. the tricky part is that sometimes we hang on to those survival skills far beyond when we need them; what we once used to get though something difficult can shift into our standard mode of operation, putting our systems in overdrive (or park). we can find ourselves hanging on to coping skills that were useful and often brilliant when we were in the thick of it, but that now hold us back from where weâ€™re trying to go. â€¢what are you hanging on to that you no longer need? â€¢what can you show gratitude toward and say farewell to? â€¢how can you honor what youâ€™ve learned and make space for healing and growth?

@radiohelsinki @katyturnbc @huffpostitalia @foxnews - bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking â€˜ugh. totally uglyâ€™ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think itâ€™s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people donâ€™t necessarily know itâ€™s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so itâ€™s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that youâ€™re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of peopleâ€™s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldnâ€™t have seen, and couldnâ€™t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, â€œwould work for anyoneâ€. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean theyâ€™re mercenaries. theyâ€™ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

itâ€™s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing â€“ at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public â€“ our intimate family connections, our â€œlikesâ€, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole thatâ€™s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr

text:
@thejimmydoreshow @bbcnews @nbcnews @anakasparianofficial @turunsanomat wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
â€œi was lucky, i was only raped by three men.â€ -rohingya survivor.

the burmese military systematically uses rape as an instrument of terror against its ethnic populations. 
thousands of testimonies and physical injuries bare witness to the assaults launched by the junta. 
the un report describes the attacks. the burmese army would enter villages late at night, â€œthe operations were designed to instil immediate terror, with people woken by intense rapid weapon fire, explosions or the shouts and screams of villagers. structures were set ablaze (and locked with people still inside), and tatmadaw soldiers fired their guns indiscriminately into houses and fields, and at villagers.â€ men unable to get away were often tortured, or forced to become porters for the army, many of which were killed after a few months. women and girls were separated, gang-raped in front of one another by dozens of soldiers for hours at a time, and then killed or bodies severely mutilated. 
i have had the privilege to interview and work with the ethnic women in the contested states of burma. hear their horrific recounts. but what breaks my heart, is how normalized this has become. they are able to talk of the rape theyâ€™ve witnessed or experienced in such a casual way due to the sheer numbers of women they know who have experienced the trauma. rape has become almost as expected as rain during the monsoon season. 
the burmese military carries out these hellacious crimes against humanity with total impunity, and as the united nations reports, â€œit consistently fails to attribute responsibility, thereby reinforcing its message to troops that they will face no consequences.â€ i beg for the international community: such as individual nation-states, the united nations and the international criminal court to come forward and hold accountable those responsible for the systematic use of rape, ethnic cleansing, and genocide in the contested states of burma.

report: https://www.ohchr.org/documents/hrbodies/hrcouncil/ffm-myanmar/a_hrc_39_64.pdf (note:to protect the identity of the women i interviewed and those i work with, these are not personal photos but those already cleared and published.)

text:
@radiohelsinki @katyturnbc @huffpostitalia @foxnews in his first post-white house interviews, steve bannon, the rightwing ideologue who helped propel donald trump to the white house, made clear that he had no intention of going quietly. - iâ€™ve got my hands back on my weapons, the former white house chief strategist, who returned as executive chairman of breitbart news late friday afternoon, told the weekly standard. - i built a f***ing machine at breitbart. and now iâ€™m about to go back, knowing what i know, and weâ€™re about to rev that machine up. and rev it up we will do.

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trumpâ€™s election, trumpeted the return of their â€œpopulist heroâ€ on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publicationâ€™s announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if thereâ€™s any confusion out there, let me clear it up: iâ€™m leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents â€“ on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

julia carrie wong
the guardian

text:
@radiohelsinki @katyturnbc @huffpostitalia @foxnews in his first post-white house interviews, steve bannon, the rightwing ideologue who helped propel donald trump to the white house, made clear that he had no intention of going quietly. - iâ€™ve got my hands back on my weapons, the former white house chief strategist, who returned as executive chairman of breitbart news late friday afternoon, told the weekly standard. - i built a f***ing machine at breitbart. and now iâ€™m about to go back, knowing what i know, and weâ€™re about to rev that machine up. and rev it up we will do.

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trumpâ€™s election, trumpeted the return of their â€œpopulist heroâ€ on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publicationâ€™s announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if thereâ€™s any confusion out there, let me clear it up: iâ€™m leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents â€“ on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

julia carrie wong
the guardian

@regran_ed from @warif_ng -  december 07 | day 13

feeling safe again after a sexual assault can be one of the most challenging aspects of healing, and is often a struggle for survivors. facilities for care and support are necessary to help survivors through this time.

the warif centre is a safe haven where survivors are helped in a step by step approach through the initial traumatic phase of their experience and the necessary follow-up visits.  available to all, we provide medical care, psycho social counselling, legal services  and access to shelters totally free of charge.

share our stories, repost, tag someone and join us in the #orangetheworldwithwarif campaign as we participate in the #16daysofactivism against gender based violence.

warif centre: 6, turton street, off thorburn avenue, yaba, lagos.
warif confidential helpline: 08092100009

text:
@cnn @nyt.fi @huffpost wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin

tweet_full:
@cnn @nyt.fi @huffpost wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

text:
"in times of trauma, like a sexual assault, you donâ€™t think clearly and you donâ€™t file memories correctly all the time. there are things i can't remember -- and things i'll never forget"
.

meet trauma informed yoga teacher @yoginijulie sharing her #yogasavedmylife story with us. these are her words ğŸ’š
.
. "i remember what i was wearing -- a baggy sweatshirt, and jeans. it was a weeknight, and we were going to watch a movie. as i relaxed with my feet up on my friend's couch, he brought me a tall, fizzy, orange-flavored drink. then itâ€™s all a blank -- until i woke up later on his bed. he was on top of me. i registered what was happening, but paralyzed and terrified, i passed out again
.
i drove back to my apartment later, called my parents, and moved home. the police wouldn't even take my story. i talked to my therapist, and that was helpful, but i still struggled with anxiety attacks and bouts of severe depression. but then i found what would change me forever -- yoga
.
it started as simple exercises, then become a daily practice of meditation, mindfulness, spirituality, and reconnecting with my body.i hated my body -- i wanted to escape it, to hide away and live in my head
.

trauma-sensitive yoga, however, teaches how to be gentle with yourself, to be in the moment, and find that comfort and healing once again. it was absolutely life-changing for me. i even reached a point where i was able to forgive my attacker, inside myself, and stop the cycle of hate. i studied tsy as much as i could, and became a certified teacher. now i am thrilled to be able to help and guide other women on their own path to healing. i truly feel this is my purpose in life
.

it happened to me too, like it happens to too many others. but nobody took anything away from me. iâ€™m still whole and iâ€™m complete. and now, with yoga as a tool and a lifestyle, i'm stronger than ever before ğŸ™ julie
.
.

"you don't realise how much you have neglected yourself until you make yourself a priority again" 
i spent so many years neglected myself, not getting my nails done, not doing the things i enjoyed, all because he consumed all my time and energy. i was slowly giving up all the "normal" things, and i was becoming unrecognisable, i became someone that wasnt me!

learning to love yourself after abuse, is one of the first steps to recovery. put yourself first and when you start doing the things you stopped, you will start to heal.

text:
feature friday
afda film hits home

afda port elizabeth honours graduation film, isikhalo: the outcry, directed by loren buchner and sisanda dyantyi, is gaining a great deal of traction for highlighting a pertinent issue facing women in sa â€“ spousal rape.

the film introduces ciki, a young women who grew up in a small hamburg village who marries a suburban high school teacher. after moving to ntselamanzi township with her bantu, she discovers her husband is not the man she imagined him to be. supported by her fellow stokvel friends, ciki finally stands up to his archaic interpretation of cultural standards, and so begins a journey of courageous self-discovery â€œthe day that i knew when â€œisikhaloâ€ was going to make an impact, was when the numetro projectionist, a middle-aged male, came out of the projecting room to congratulate and hug the crew after the test screening of the film before the afda graduation festival.â€ says mark wilby, afda pe head of postgraduate studies.

feature friday
afda film hits home

afda port elizabeth honours graduation film, isikhalo: the outcry, directed by loren buchner and sisanda dyantyi, is gaining a great deal of traction for highlighting a pertinent issue facing women in sa â€“ spousal rape.

the film introduces ciki, a young women who grew up in a small hamburg village who marries a suburban high school teacher. after moving to ntselamanzi township with her bantu, she discovers her husband is not the man she imagined him to be. supported by her fellow stokvel friends, ciki finally stands up to his archaic interpretation of cultural standards, and so begins a journey of courageous self-discovery â€œthe day that i knew when â€œisikhaloâ€ was going to make an impact, was when the numetro projectionist, a middle-aged male, came out of the projecting room to congratulate and hug the crew after the test screening of the film before the afda graduation festival.â€ says mark wilby, afda pe head of postgraduate studies.

text:
yesterday was national day of remembrance on violence against women. 
it's also happens to be the day i was re-victimized, by questions like, "well was there alcohol involved?" like that is even a relevant factor. 
i didn't acknowledge it yesterday, because like so many victims of violence, i was ashamed. 
but i'm over it. 
part of being so open about sharing my journey, the good, the bad and the super ugly, is  that i know there are other women out there, reading my posts and seeing themselves in them. 
i know this because every once in a while, someone reaches out and says "thank you for helping me know i am not alone." and it fills my heart. 
my journey is about healing. healing my body, my mind, and my spirit. 
if you are a survivor of violence, i want you to know this; ğŸ”¹you are not alone ğŸ”¹it is not your fault. ever. in no way shape or form is what happened to you your fault. period. ğŸ”¹ you will come out the other side of this. it's going to be an ugly ride, but you are a survivor. ğŸ”¹ you are loved. and in those moments you don't feel it, know that as someone who understands, i love you.

thank you, thank you, thank you @sipinsoma @danielleperrotta for allowing me to tell the beginning of my journey of #survivorship, which is an ongoing journey to this day. please listen to my @sipinsoma podcast interview that just dropped yesterday via my linktree link in bio ğŸ‘†ğŸ½where you can also purchase my novella the survivors club for $6 ($5 goes to charity). the holidays can be triggering and thereâ€™s a ton of family time that can be difficult for survivors of child abuse. take time out for yourself. breath, meditate, and remind yourself that you can create the holiday experience that you want in little waysâ€”whether it is by decorating your house they way you wanted it to look as a  child but couldnâ€™t (thatâ€™s me! âœ‹ğŸ½) or if you want to play certain music, make special food, create a new tradition with your kids, whatever! carve out a way to make it yours and be in the moment about it. i am thankful for my community of support and for amazing people like @danielleperrotta who truly let me shine during this interview ğŸ˜˜

@radiohelsinki @katyturnbc @huffpostitalia @foxnews in his first post-white house interviews, steve bannon, the rightwing ideologue who helped propel donald trump to the white house, made clear that he had no intention of going quietly. - iâ€™ve got my hands back on my weapons, the former white house chief strategist, who returned as executive chairman of breitbart news late friday afternoon, told the weekly standard. - i built a f***ing machine at breitbart. and now iâ€™m about to go back, knowing what i know, and weâ€™re about to rev that machine up. and rev it up we will do.

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trumpâ€™s election, trumpeted the return of their â€œpopulist heroâ€ on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publicationâ€™s announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if thereâ€™s any confusion out there, let me clear it up: iâ€™m leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents â€“ on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

julia carrie wong
the guardian

text:
@radiohelsinki @katyturnbc @huffpostitalia @foxnews in his first post-white house interviews, steve bannon, the rightwing ideologue who helped propel donald trump to the white house, made clear that he had no intention of going quietly. - iâ€™ve got my hands back on my weapons, the former white house chief strategist, who returned as executive chairman of breitbart news late friday afternoon, told the weekly standard. - i built a f***ing machine at breitbart. and now iâ€™m about to go back, knowing what i know, and weâ€™re about to rev that machine up. and rev it up we will do.

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trumpâ€™s election, trumpeted the return of their â€œpopulist heroâ€ on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publicationâ€™s announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if thereâ€™s any confusion out there, let me clear it up: iâ€™m leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents â€“ on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

julia carrie wong
the guardian

@huffposttaste @foxnews @nytimes - bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking â€˜ugh. totally uglyâ€™ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think itâ€™s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people donâ€™t necessarily know itâ€™s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so itâ€™s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that youâ€™re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of peopleâ€™s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldnâ€™t have seen, and couldnâ€™t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, â€œwould work for anyoneâ€. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean theyâ€™re mercenaries. theyâ€™ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

itâ€™s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing â€“ at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public â€“ our intimate family connections, our â€œlikesâ€, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole thatâ€™s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
my sincerest thank you to everyone that watched, supported & shared. i have a love for a number of things but scripting, directing and film production are absolutely at the top of that list! to aisha and the other survivors you will hear as the series continues i thank you for trusting me with your stories! i received word last night that while a family was watching your story a young girl came forward about something that had secretly transpired in her life! this matter is so much bigger than us and it is my desire that it will continue to liberate the hearts that are heavy & bound! this is a conversation that can no longer wait. it's definitely a hard one but somebody has to have it! lastly, congratulations to all those who have begun this journey! this is freedom!

1.800.770.1650 or text 'iowahelp' to 201-21.

"so, kamala harris, senator from california, former attorney general of california, she has been an early lead [for presidential nomination]. iâ€™ve said that sheâ€™s probably the scariest person right now, scariest in that we donâ€™t know much about her. sheâ€™s clearly pretty intelligent. she checks off the intersectional boxes of the left," he said. "just today, just out today, thereâ€™s a negative news story about her." knowles explained how larry wallace, a former senior advisor to harris while she served as ag, settled a $400,000 lawsuit for gender discrimination and harassment during harrisâ€™ transition from the california attorney generalâ€™s office to the senate. "thatâ€™s my tax money, anyone else whoâ€™s listening in california, thatâ€™s your tax money paying that out," he said. "and where it gets pretty dicey for her is that they asked kamala harris what about this major lawsuit almost half a million dollars for one of your senior advisors sexually harassing some woman, and harrisâ€™s office said they had no awareness of it. they had no idea what was going on." "this is not believable," he stressed. "this is not believable at all. this guy has worked with her in all of her major jobs, and this lawsuit occurred on her watch. so, either sheâ€™s lying, which obviously she is, or sheâ€™s totally incompetent. the office is totally incompetent if theyâ€™ve never heard of this. but itâ€™s just not possible." knowles discussed how harrisâ€™ successor to california ag would have been the one who settled the suit, adding even more doubt to the story that the democrat lawmaker knew nothing about it. and to make matters worse, the alleged victim is forbidden to go to the media with her story.
this, said knowles, is the highest form of hypocrisy: "kamala harris positioned herself as the champion of the #metoo movement. kamala harris was there going after brett kavanaugh during all of those hearings. she believes christine blasey ford. she opposes brett kavanaugh. all but painted brett kavanaugh to be some gang rapist. and we need the truth to be heard!"
-the daily wire
