text:
if you think your voice doesnâ€™t matter, that you canâ€™t make an impact with your actions, guess again.

timeâ€™s up legal defense fund, a gofundme campaign that raises money for legal defense funds for victims of sexual assault and harassment in the workplace raised more than $22 million this year â€” the biggest fundraiser in the entire history of gofundme.

although this post celebrates a small but pivotal shift in the #metoomovement, this is a storm with ever changing winds and fierce conditions. and it doesnâ€™t only apply to women, men are just now finding the courage to break their silence as well.

isnâ€™t this an uncomfortable conversation to be having amid the selfies and product flat lays that i myself celebrate everyday? 
yes, but if i canâ€™t use my platform to shine a light on real fucking issues when it counts, it blatantly kicks dirt on my right to freely post all my floaty poetry, playfulness and curated photographs that people before me fought so hard for.

while iâ€™ve never had a personal story to add to the #metoo conversation, iâ€™ve listened with my stomach in knots, as both friends and strangers have told me theirs over the last few years.

itâ€™s easy to slouch into the shadows. walking tall is hard, and even though it might take all your strength just to put one foot in front of the other, youâ€™re still moving forward. please know that you can still be brave even though your hands are shaking. youâ€™re not alone.

when i saw this...it took me forever to find the one right side up...but as soon as i did...they all were facing up...now when i look at them it's a mix...some are up...some are down. i think it's a beautiful analogy for life....there is always a different perspective...a different way to look at things...the minute we close ourselves off to it...is the day we limit ourselves and our world.
regardless of your take on theğŸµ baby it''s cold outsideğŸµban...
it's like i can see both sides...my whole life i've loved that song...for real. but now with what's happening in todays world...you read it and just can see how the lyrics could be teaching our boys n girls not so great of a
 message.  if a girl does say no to you...umm multiple times... it was written in 1944...just different times. i'll still enjoy the song...nostalgia growing up if anything...but i'm not so closed off that i will be  throwing a fit if it's not on the 
radio anymore. 
it's still available on youtube, spotify, pandora etc 
it's like this picture....once you see it...someone could ask you 10 times how are the plates facing? down...down...do..ohhh upp..wait how can that be?
it all gets flipped and you start wondering how did we see it the other way so clearly.....but the people who don't care to see both sides..the ones that won't acknowledge there might be an other side that holds merit...
the second we start being afraid to speak up about what could be wrong,say what hurts us..scares..us...gasp! offends us....is the day we ....
ohhh wait we r already there....there was more outrage on a 1944 christmas song than children being locked up in cages....separated from their parents or the fact women were coming forward saying "this happened to me." #metoo
maybe before jumping to the side you think is so clear....we should just try...try...try
 to see it through someones
 else's life... because ironically if you had 2 people arguing upside down and right side up....they would both be right.

text:
how is voyeurism defined under the ipc?

section 354c of the ipc criminalises the act of voyeurism. it defines it as a man watching or capturing the image of a woman engaged in a private act in circumstances where she would usually not expect to be observed by the perpetrator or by any other person on the orders of the perpetrator or the distribution of an image so captured by the perpetrator.

what is the punishment for an act of voyeurism?

the punishment for committing this offence is simple or rigorous imprisonment of 1 to 3 years and a fine. repeated offenders are punished with simple or rigorous imprisonment of 3 to 7 years and a fine.
.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think itâ€™s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people donâ€™t necessarily know itâ€™s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so itâ€™s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that youâ€™re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of peopleâ€™s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldnâ€™t have seen, and couldnâ€™t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, â€œwould work for anyoneâ€. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean theyâ€™re mercenaries. theyâ€™ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

the guardian

text:
â­ï¸â­ï¸â­ï¸â­ï¸â­ï¸ i was worried this would be a 250-page rant. i was worried it would make me even angrier, if that was possible. i shouldnâ€™t have worried. i want everyone to read this book. the women who feel angry will feel so validated; the men who are wondering why we are so pissed will have some insights. and all of us will be given an overdue history lesson and a much needed correction on how we view womenâ€™s anger in this country.

she has done her research. she gives example after example of womenâ€™s rage leading directly to positive political change that benefits us all. women are not given the credit they deserve in our history books. we hear about white menâ€™s anger as being a vital part of our nationâ€™s founding, an admirable force for good. give me liberty or give me death! white men angrily broke free of imperialist control, then built a nation on slavery and the oppression of women, disenfranchising the majority of the population while holding literally all the power. women arenâ€™t mentioned in the constitution, not once. weâ€™ve had to fight for every right we enjoy today. and the fight is not over.

she talks in depth about the #metoo movement. she also addresses the need for white women to look at how women of color have been angry for a long time. while most of us got politically engaged after the 2016 election, women of color have been fighting against a white patriarchy all along. we cannot just come in and take over the resistance and act like we invented the idea. .

we also need to recognize that white women are still part of the problem. the majority of us voted for donald trump and for misogynist candidates like roy moore. black women overwhelmingly did not. we need to take a hard look at how white women are willing to take the benefits and the protection of the white patriarchal power structure at the expense of all oppressed people. this is a reckoning that is long overdue.

sometimes a book comes along that perfectly captures the political and societal moment as itâ€™s morphing into a movement. traister has done an excellent job here. i highly recommend reading it; donâ€™t be afraid of your anger.

@thejimmydoreshow @bbcnews @nbcnews @anakasparianofficial @turunsanomat in his first post-white house interviews, steve bannon, the rightwing ideologue who helped propel donald trump to the white house, made clear that he had no intention of going quietly. - iâ€™ve got my hands back on my weapons, the former white house chief strategist, who returned as executive chairman of breitbart news late friday afternoon, told the weekly standard. - i built a f***ing machine at breitbart. and now iâ€™m about to go back, knowing what i know, and weâ€™re about to rev that machine up. and rev it up we will do.

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trumpâ€™s election, trumpeted the return of their â€œpopulist heroâ€ on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publicationâ€™s announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if thereâ€™s any confusion out there, let me clear it up: iâ€™m leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents â€“ on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

julia carrie wong
the guardian

it's time to be unashamedly you!
